OK, the `{` is only consumed through `p.expect(T!['{'])` in block parsing. When `{` appears in a declaration value, it goes through recovery as a `CSS_BOGUS_PROPERTY_VALUE`.

Let me try a different, simpler approach. Instead of adding state tracking, I can modify the recovery for `GenericComponentValueList` to set a flag in the parser state when `{` or `}` is encountered during recovery. But actually, that's complex because recovery happens across many paths.

Let me think about this more simply. The real issue is in the validation of the speculative parse in `DeclarationOrRuleList::parse_element`. After the speculative declaration parse "succeeds", we need a better check. 

Actually, the simplest fix: in the recovery for `GenericComponentValueList`, when the parser encounters `{` or `}`, set `encountered_curly_brace_in_value = true`. Then in the validation check for speculative declaration parsing, also check that this flag is false.

Wait, but we'd also need to reset this flag between speculative attempts. Let me look at `try_parse`:

```rust
let checkpoint = p.checkpoint();
let old_speculative_parsing = std::mem::replace(&mut p.state_mut().speculative_parsing, true);
let res = func(p);
p.state_mut().speculative_parsing = old_speculative_parsing;
if res.is_err() {
    p.rewind(checkpoint);
}
res
```

When `try_parse` succeeds, it doesn't rewind. So the flag would persist. When it fails, it rewinds. But we need to reset the flag before each try_parse call.

Alternatively, a simpler approach: don't add a state flag at all. Instead, after the speculative declaration parse, check if the parsed tokens included `{` before the final `;`. We can check this by looking at what `p.last()` is and what was between the start and end.

Actually, let me step back and think about what the simplest effective fix is.

Looking at the code in `DeclarationOrRuleList::parse_element` again:

```rust
let declaration = try_parse(p, |p| {
    let declaration = parse_any_declaration_with_semicolon(p);
    if p.state().encountered_if_function {
        return Err(());
    }
    let valid = matches!(p.last(), Some(T![;])) || p.at(self.end_kind);
    if valid { Ok(declaration) } else { Err(()) }
});
```

The `valid` check is too lenient. After parsing `div:first-of-type { color: black; }` as a declaration, `p.last()` returns `;` because the semicolon inside the rule block is consumed.

One approach: check if any `{` was consumed between the checkpoint and the current position. We can do this by also tracking `encountered_curly_brace_in_value` in the parser state.

Let me implement this approach. I'll set the flag in the `GenericComponentValueList::recover` when the current token is `{` (L_CURLY).

