Now I see the critical detail! In `ParseNodeList::parse_list`, line 59-60:
```rust
while !p.at(EOF) && !self.is_at_list_end(p)
{
    progress.assert_progressing(p);
    let parsed_element = self.parse_element(p);
    if self.recover(p, parsed_element).is_err() {
        break;
    }
}
```

So `is_at_list_end` is checked BEFORE `parse_element`. If `p.at(T!['}'])` is true in `is_at_list_end`, the loop exits BEFORE parsing the element. So `}` should NOT go through `parse_element` or `recover`.

But my debug output shows `encountered_curly_brace_in_value during spec parse at '}'`. This means `}` IS going through recovery somehow.

Wait, but the `GenericComponentValueList` is parsed INSIDE the spec declaration parse. The `GenericComponentValueList` has its own `ParseNodeList` implementation. Inside its `parse_list`, the same pattern applies: `is_at_list_end` is checked before `parse_element`. And `GenericComponentValueList::is_at_list_end` checks `p.at_ts(self.end_set)` where end set includes `}`.

Hmm, but could the issue be that the declaration property value uses `parse_property_value_with_end_set` which instantiates `GenericComponentValueList` with a custom end set? Let me check:

